04910nam a22007095i 9780691216065DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20211992nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912160657 a10.1515/97806912160652doi  a(DE-B1597)566868  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1995b.S6735 1992 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.43/012201 aStaiger, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aInterpreting Films :bStudies in the Historical Reception of American Cinema /cJanet Staiger. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Sources -- tPreface -- tPART ONE: THEORETICAL CONCERNS -- tChapter One The Use-Value of Reception Studies -- tChapter Two Reception Studies in Other Disciplines -- tChapter Three Reception Studies in Film and Television -- tChapter Four Toward a Historical Materialist Approach to Reception Studies -- tPART TWO: STUDIES IN THE HISTORY OF THE RECEPTION OF AMERICAN FILMS -- tChapter Five Rethinking "Primitive" Cinema: Intertextuality, the Middle-Class Audience, and Reception Studies -- tChapter Six 'The Handmaiden of Villainy": Foolish Wives, Politics, Gender Orientation, and the Other -- tChapter Seven The Birth of a Nation: Reconsidering Its Reception -- tChapter Eight The Logic of Alternative Readings: A Star Is Born -- tChapter Nine With the Compliments of the Auteur: Art Cinema and the Complexities of Its Reading Strategies -- tChapter Ten Chameleon in the Film, Chameleons in the Audience; or, Where Is Parody? The Case ofZelig -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEmploying a wide range of examples from Uncle Tom's Cabin and Birth of a Nation to Zelig and Personal Best, Janet Staiger argues that a historical examination of spectators' responses to films can make a valuable contribution to the history, criticism, and philosophy of cultural products. She maintains that as artifacts, films do not contain immanent meanings, that differences among interpretations have historical bases, and that these variations are due to social, political, and economic conditions as well as the viewers' constructed images of themselves. After proposing a theory of reception study, the author demonstrates its application mainly through analyzing the varying responses of audiences to certain films at specific moments in history. Staiger gives special attention to how questions of class, gender, sexual preference, race, and ethnicity enter into film viewers' interpretations. Her analysis reflects recent developments in post-structuralism, cognitive psychology, psychoanalysis, and cultural studies, and includes a discussion of current reader-response models in literary and film studies as well as an alternative approach for thinking about historical readers and spectators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEsthetique de la reception. 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMotion picturesxEsthetique. 0aMotion pictureszÉtats-Unis. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszÉtats-Unis. 0aReader-response criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691216065zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691216065423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691216065.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  